Vita omnium operum, ſaies Melancton; feare is the vivacity of all our actions; whatſoever wee doe without feare is dead in the very doing; and the reaſon of it is given by Solomon; 
Eccleſ. 12.13 
Officium enim eſt totius hominis; for this is the whole duty of man, to feare God, and keepe his Commandements.

As feare is a paſſion of the ſoule, you may underſtand that ſpeech of Saint John; 
               Joh. 12.42. Many of the Rulers beleeved in Chriſt, but for feare of the Jewes they did not confeſſe him, leſt they ſhould be put out of the Synagogue; for they loved the praiſe of men more then the praiſe of God: I may add, They feared the injuſtice and puniſhment of men more then the juſtice and chaſtiſement of

 God; and therfore ſayes Chriſt, Matth. 10.28. fear not them which kil the Body, but are not able to kill the ſoule, but rather feare him, who is able to deſtroy both ſoule and body in hell:
